    <section id="de-re-stress" class="project">
      <header class="project-header">
        <h2>de/re stress</h2>
        <p class="project-meta">prof. Mark Wamble <span>·</span> with Charlotte Cohen <span>·</span> Mahama Refugee Camp, Rwanda</p>
      </header>

      <div class="project-content">
        <div class="project-row">
          <div class="image-placeholder">stress-model-1.jpg</div>
          <div class="image-placeholder">stress-model-2.jpg</div>
        </div>

        <div class="project-row">
          <div class="project-row-text">
            <p class="highlight">This project explores the structural logic of plywood through the lens of stitch-and-glue kayak construction. Using thin veneer to mimic the behavior of full-scale plywood, the scale model bends, folds, and joins material in tension and compression.</p>
            <p>Strategic perforations relieve internal stress while preserving strength, allowing the form to take shape without breaking, and each panel is stitched together with synthetic sinew.</p>
            <p>The resulting structure, both delicate and resilient, demonstrates the surprising load-bearing capacity of curved wood, successfully supporting over 100 pounds despite its minimal material footprint.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="project-images-col">
            <div class="image-placeholder">stress-detail-1.jpg</div>
            <div class="image-placeholder">stress-detail-2.jpg</div>
            <div class="image-placeholder">stress-detail-3.jpg</div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="project-row">
          <div class="project-row-text">
            <p>The structure is designed to be constructed without the use of power tools. The system echoes the technology of two precedents: the stitch and glue kayak and Patkau Architect's Winnipeg Skating Structures—the idea of a low-resource, almost DIY construction process, featuring prefabricated CNC-milled panels and sinew hand-stitched seams.</p>
          </div>
          <div class="image-placeholder">stress-precedent.jpg</div>
        </div>

        <p class="highlight">DE/RE STRESS applies the vertically-rigid and monoclastic properties of plywood to create a system of monolithic forms. Each module holds the profile of a rectangle and footprint of an oval: it is in the initial translation and stressing between these two geometries that structural rigidity begins to arise. This tension is de-stressed by exterior relief cuts.</p>

        <p>At a smaller scale, each face is comprised of several surfaces: each bent along their own axis as if they are extracted from slivers of a cone. The system of surfaces meeting at precise angles defines the structural shell.</p>

